\"|1252\u20131269||15 August 1279||Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|| [[Elisabeth of Brabant, Duchess of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Elisabeth of Brabant]]<br/>1254<br/>no children<br><br>[[Alexia of Montferrat]]<br/>1263<br/>seven children|| Shared rule with his brother John. In 1269 divided the land with him, and became Prince of Brunswick.\n|-bgcolor=#fff\n|[[John, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|John I]] || ||1242||13 December 1277||Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg || [[Liutgard of Holstein|Liutgard of Holstein-Itzehoe]]<br/>1265<br/>five children||Shared rule with his brother Albert. In 1269 divided the land with him, and became Prince of Luneburg.\n|-\n|colspan=8|All Welf lines continued to bear the title \"Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg\" between the division of 1269 and the end of the Holy Roman Empire in 1806. This was an additional title to the representation of their actual territorial lordship. However, as this is list of rulers, the list goes beyond the use of the title, going through all generations until the end of the noble family representation in the land, in 1918.\n|-bgcolor=#FFDEAD\n|[[Albert I, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Albert I ''the Tall'']] ||[[File:Herzog Albrecht I.jpg|100px]] ||1236||1269\u20131279||15 August 1279||[[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Brunswick]]|| [[Elisabeth of Brabant, Duchess of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Elisabeth of Brabant]]<br/>1254<br/>no children<br><br>[[Alexia of Montferrat]]<br/>1263<br/>seven children|| In 1269 became Prince of Wolfenbuttel.\n|-bgcolor=#F8F8D8\n|[[John, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|John I]] || ||1242||1269-1277||13 December 1277||[[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] || [[Liutgard of Holstein, Duchess of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Liutgard of Holstein-Itzehoe]]<br/>1265<br/>five children||Shared rule with his brother Albert. In 1269 divided the land with him, and became Prince of Luneburg.\n|-bgcolor=#F8F8D8\n|''[[Albert I, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Albert I ''the Tall'']]''<br/>(regent) ||[[File:Herzog Albrecht I.jpg|100px|center]] ||1236||1277\u20131279||15 August 1279||[[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] || [[Elisabeth of Brabant, Duchess of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Elisabeth of Brabant]]<br/>1254<br/>no children<br><br>[[Alexia of Montferrat]]<br/>1263<br/>seven children\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Regents on behalf of their nephew\n|-bgcolor=#F8F8D8\n|''[[Conrad of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg, Prince-Bishop of Verden]]''<br/>(regent) ||||Before 1279||1277\u20131282||After 1282||[[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] || \n|-bgcolor=#F8F8D8\n|[[Otto II, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Otto II ''the Strict'']] ||[[File:Bomann-Museum Skulptur Otto II. der Strenge, Herzog zu Braunschweig und L\u00fcneburg, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg 1277-1330, mit von der Schmalstieg-GmbH restauriertem Schloss Celle.jpg|100px|center]] ||1266||1282-1330||10 April 1330||[[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] || [[Matilda of Bavaria, Duchess of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Matilda of Bavaria]]<br/>1288<br/>five children||His rule was marked by several feuds, financed by pledges (Verpf\u00e4ndungen), involving border and property disputes with his neighbours. Otto restricted the rights of the knights and safeguarded public order.\n\n|-bgcolor=\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Henry I, Duke of Brunswick-Grubenhagen|Henry I ''the Admirable'']]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\n|rowspan=\"2\"|August 1267\n|bgcolor=#FFDEAD|1279\u20131291\n|rowspan=\"2\"|7 September 1322\n|bgcolor=#FFDEAD|[[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Brunswick]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Agnes of Meissen]]<br/>1282<br/>sixteen children\n|rowspan=\"7\"| Sons of Albert I, ruled jointly. In 1291 divided the land: Henry received Grubenhagen, William Wolfenb\u00fcttel and Albert G\u00f6ttingen. William died without descendants, and Albert reunited his land  with his brother's. \n|-bgcolor=#B3B7FF\n||1291\u20131322||[[Principality of Grubenhagen|Grubenhagen]] \n|-bgcolor=\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[William I, Duke of Brunswick-