ry received Grubenhagen, William Wolfenb\u00fcttel and Albert G\u00f6ttingen. William died without descendants, and Albert reunited his land  with his brother's. \n|-bgcolor=#B3B7FF\n||1291\u20131322||[[Principality of Grubenhagen|Grubenhagen]] \n|-bgcolor=\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[William I, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|William I]] \n|rowspan=\"2\"| \n|rowspan=\"2\"|1270\n|bgcolor=#FFDEAD|1279-1291\n|rowspan=\"2\"|30 September 1292\n|bgcolor=#FFDEAD|[[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Brunswick]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Elisabeth of Hesse, Duchess of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Elisabeth of Hesse]]<br/>190<br/>no children \n|-bgcolor=#D8F8D8\n||1291\u20131292||[[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Wolfenb\u00fcttel]]\n|-bgcolor=\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Albert II, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Albert II ''the Fat'']] \n|rowspan=\"3\"| \n|rowspan=\"3\"|1268\n|bgcolor=#FFDEAD|1279-1291\n|rowspan=\"3\"|22 September 1318\n|bgcolor=#FFDEAD|[[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Brunswick]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Rixa of Werle|Rixa of Mecklenburg-Werle]]<br/>1284<br/>ten children\n|-bgcolor=#88EEEE\n||1291\u20131292||[[Principality of G\u00f6ttingen|G\u00f6ttingen]]\n|-\n||1292\u20131318||[[Principality of G\u00f6ttingen|G\u00f6ttingen]] and [[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Wolfenb\u00fcttel]]\n|-\n|[[Otto the Mild, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Otto III ''the Mild'']] || [[File:Otto der Milde.jpg|100px]] ||24 June 1292\n||1318\u20131344||30 August 1344||[[Principality of G\u00f6ttingen|G\u00f6ttingen]] and [[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Wolfenb\u00fcttel]]||[[Judith of Hesse]]<br/>1311<br/>no children<br><br>[[Agnes of Brandenburg, Duchess of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Agnes of Brandenburg-Salzwedel]]<br/>1319<br/>no children\n|rowspan=\"5\"|Sons of Albert II, ruled jointly. After Otto's death Magnus and Ernest divided the land: Magnus received Wolfenb\u00fcttel and Ernest G\u00f6ttingen.\n|-bgcolor=\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Magnus I, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Magnus I ''the Pious'']] \n|rowspan=\"2\"| \n|rowspan=\"2\"|1304||1318\u20131344\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1369||[[Principality of G\u00f6ttingen|G\u00f6ttingen]] and [[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Wolfenb\u00fcttel]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Sophia of Brandenburg-Stendal]]<br/>1327<br/>eight children\n|-bgcolor=#D8F8D8\n||1344-1369|| [[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Wolfenb\u00fcttel]]\n|-bgcolor=\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Ernest I, Duke of Brunswick-G\u00f6ttingen|Ernest I]] \n|rowspan=\"2\"| \n|rowspan=\"2\"|1305||1318\u20131344\n|rowspan=\"2\"|24 April 1367||[[Principality of G\u00f6ttingen|G\u00f6ttingen]] and [[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Wolfenb\u00fcttel]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Elizabeth of Hesse, Duchess of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Elizabeth of Hesse]]<br/>1337<br/>three children\n|-bgcolor=#88EEEE\n||1344\u20131367||[[Principality of G\u00f6ttingen|G\u00f6ttingen]] \n|-bgcolor=#B3B7FF\n|[[Henry II, Duke of Brunswick-Grubenhagen|Henry II]] ||||Before 1296||1322\u20131351||After 1351||[[Principality of Grubenhagen|Grubenhagen]] || [[Jutta of Brandenburg-Stendal]]<br>1318<br>four children<br><br>[[Helvis of Ibelin]]<br>1324<br>six children\n|rowspan=\"4\"| Sons of Henry I, ruled jointly. \n|-bgcolor=#B3B7FF\n|[[Ernest I, Duke of Brunswick-Grubenhagen|Ernest II]] ||||1297||1322\u20131361||9 March 1361||[[Principality of Grubenhagen|Grubenhagen]] || [[Adelheid of Everstein-Polle]]<br/>June 1335<br/>nine children\n|-bgcolor=#B3B7FF\n|[[William, Duke of Brunswick-Grubenhagen|William II]] ||||1298||1322\u20131360||1360||[[Principality of Grubenhagen|Grubenhagen]] ||''Unmarried'' \n|-bgcolor=#B3B7FF\n|[[John I, Duke of Brunswick-Grubenhagen|John II]] ||||Before 1296||1322\u20131325||After 1367||[[Principality of Grubenhagen|Grubenhagen]] || ''Unmarried''\n|-bgcolor=#F8F8D8\n|[[Otto III, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Otto IV]] ||||1296||1330\u20131352||19 August 1352||[[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] || [[Matilda of Mecklenburg]]<br/>1311<br/>three children\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Sons of Otto II, ruled jointly. After Otto's death in 1352, William ruled alone. His death without descendants precipitated the [[L\u00fcneburg War of Succession]] in 1370.\n|-bgcolor=#F8F8D8\n|[[William II, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|William III ''the Elder'']] ||[[File:Wilhelmvonbraunschweiglueneburg(gest.1369).jpg|100px]]||c.1300||1330\u20131369||23 November 1369||[[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] || [[Hedwig of Ravensberg]]<br>7 April 1328<br>one child<br><br>Maria<br>After 1387<br>one child<br><br>[[Sophia of Anhalt-Bernburg]]<br>12 March 1346<br>no children<br><br>[[Agnes of Saxe-Lauenburg]]<br>1363<br>no children \n|-bgcolor=#B3B7FF\n|[[Albert I, Duke of Brunswick-Grubenhagen|Albert III]] ||||c.1339||1361\u20131383||1383||[[Principality of Grubenhagen|Grubenhagen]] || [[Agnes of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg, Duchess of Brunswick-Grubenhagen|Agnes of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg]]<br/>c.1380?<br/>one child\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Sons of Ernest II, ruled jointly. John abdicated 1364 to join the clergy and Albert became sole ruler.\n|-bgcolor=#B3B7FF\n|[[John II, Duke of Brunswick-Grubenhagen|John III]] ||||c.1339||1361\u20131364||18 January 1401||[[Principality of Grubenhagen|Grubenhagen]] || [[Adelheid of Everstein-Polle]]<br/>June 1335<br/>nine children\n|-bgcolor=#88EEEE\n|[[Otto I, Duke of Brunswick-G\u00f6ttingen|Otto V ''the Evil'']] ||[[File:Otto der Quade 001.JPG|100px]] ||1330||1367\u20131394||13 November 1394||[[Principality of G\u00f6ttingen|G\u00f6ttingen]] ||[[Margarethe of J\u00fclich-Berg]]<br/>1379<br/>two children||\n|-bgcolor=\n|[[Magnus II, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Magnus II ''of the Necklace'']] ''(Torquatus)''||[[File:Magnustorquatus gesamt.jpg|100px]]||1304||1369\u20131373||25 July 1373|| [[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Wolfenb\u00fcttel]] and [[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] ||[[Katherine of Anhalt-Bernburg]]<br/>1327<br/>eight children|| Inherited Wolfenb\u00fcttel from his father. However, the [[L\u00fcneburg War of Succession]] allowed his succession also in this duchy. However, the War of Succession brought, after his death, the dukes of Saxe-Wittenberg to the government.\n|-bgcolor=#D8F8D8\n|[[Frederick I, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Frederick I]] || ||1357||1373\u20131400||5 June 1400|| [[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Wolfenb\u00fcttel]]||[[Anna of Saxe-Wittenberg]]<br/>1386<br/>two children||Fulfilling the agreement of Hanover, married the daughter of the Duke Wenceslaus of Saxe-Wittenberg.\n|-bgcolor=#F8F8D8\n|colspan=8| After the death of [[Magnus II, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Magnus II with the Necklace]], a treaty (the Reconciliation of Hanover) was agreed between the widow of Magnus II and her sons and the claimers, [[Albert of Saxe-Wittenberg, Duke of L\u00fcneburg|Albert of Saxe-Wittenberg]] and his uncle [[Wenceslaus I, Duke of Saxe-Wittenberg|Duke Wenceslaus I of Saxe-Wittenberg]]: the estates of the Principality were to pay homage both to the Welfs and to the Ascanians, and the two noble houses would govern the state alternately. Initially, the land would be given to the two Ascanians from Wittenberg, and after their death it would go to the sons of the fallen Duke Magnus II. After their death, rule of the Principality was to revert to the Ascanians. In order to underpin the agreement, in 1374 Albert of Saxe-L\u00fcneburg married Catharina, the widow of Magnus II.  The treaty also envisaged the creation of a statutory body representing the estates, which was to supervise the treaty. However, 1373\u20131388 would be the only period in which a Brunswick-Luneburg land was not ruled by a Welf. \n|-bgcolor=#F8F8D8\n|[[Albert of Saxe-Wittenberg, Duke of L\u00fcneburg|Albert IV]] ([[Ascanian]])||[[File:Albrechtvonsachsenwittenberg.jpg|100px]]||before 1350||1373\u20131385||28 June 1385|| [[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] ||[[Katherine of Anhalt-Bernburg]]<br/>10 November 1373<br>[[Hanover]]<br>11 July 1374<br>[[Celle]]<br/>one child|| Inherited L\u00fcneburg as he was son of Elisabeth, daughter of William the Elder. To reinforce his claim married the widow of the previous duke, Katherine. Albert also moved the residence to [[Celle]] after the [[slighting]] of L\u00fcneburg Castle. With no male heirs, his co-ruler and uncle, [[Wenceslaus I, Duke of Saxe-Wittenberg|Wenceslaus I of Saxe-Wittenberg]], took the entire government of L\u00fcneburg.\n|-bgcolor=#F8F8D8\n|[[Wenceslaus I, Duke of Saxe-Wittenberg|Wenceslaus I]] ([[Ascanian]])''||[[File:WenzelISachsenWittenberg.jpg|100px]]||1337||1373\u20131388||15 May 1388|| [[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] ||[[Cecilia da Carrara]]<br/>23 January 1376<br/>six children|| Took the entire government of the duchy after the death of his nephew, the natural heir. After his death,according to the treaty, the duchy was returned to the Welfs.\n|-bgcolor=#F8F8D8\n|colspan=8| In the wake of his death, Elector Wenceslas appointed Bernard, his brother-in-law, as co-regent involved him in the government. But his younger brother [[Henry I of Brunswick|Henry]] did not agree with this ruling, and after vain attempts to reach an agreement, the fight flared up again in the spring of 1388. Elector [[Wenceslas I of Saxe-Wittenberg|Wenceslas]] had to assemble an army without the help of Bernard, supported by the town of L\u00fcneburg. From [[Winsen (Aller)|Winsen an der Aller]], he wanted to attack [[Celle]], which was held by Henry and his mother. During the preparations, however, Elector Wenceslas fell seriously ill and died shortly thereafter. According to legend, he was poisoned. L\u00fcneburg continued the preparations, formed an alliance with the [[Bishopric of Minden|Bishop of Minden]] and [[County of Schaumburg|Count of Schaumburg]] and set up his own army. On 28 May 1388, battle was joined at Winsen an der Aller; it ended in victory for [[Henry I of Brunswick|Henry]]. According to the provisions of the Treaty of Hanover from the year 1373, after the death of Wensceslas, the Principality passed to the [[House of Welf]]. In 1389, a inheritance agreement between the Welfs and the Ascanians was concluded, the treaty of 1374 was abolished, and the Principality was finally secured for the Welfs.\n|-bgcolor=#B3B7FF\n|''[[Frederick I, Duke of Brunswick-Osterode]]'' (regent)||||c.1383||1383\u20131401||28 May 1427||[[Principality of Grubenhagen|Grubenhagen]] || [[Adelaide of Anhalt-Zerbst]]<br/>c.1395?<br>one child||Brother of Albert III, regent on behalf of his nephew, Eric\n|-bgcolor=#B3B7FF\n|[[Eric I, Duke of Brunswick-Grubenhagen|Eric I ''the Winner'']] ||||c.1383||1401\u20131427||28 May 1427||[[Principality of Grubenhagen|Grubenhagen]] || [[Elisabeth of Brunswick-G\u00f6ttingen]]<br/>six children|| \n|-bgcolor=\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Henry the Mild, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Henry III the Mild]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[File:Heinrichvonbraunschweiglueneburg(gest.1416).jpg|100px]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1355\n|bgcolor=#F8F8D8|1388\u20131400\n|rowspan=\"3\"|14 October 1416\n|bgcolor=#F8F8D8| [[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] \n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Sophia of Pomerania, Duchess of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Sophia of Pomerania]]<br/>11 November 1388<br/>two children<br><br>[[Margaret of Hesse, Duchess of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Margaret of Hesse]]<br/>30 January 1409<br/>one child\n|rowspan=\"6\"| Sons of Magnus II, ruled jointly. They permanently recovered L\u00fcneburg for the Welfs. In 1400 inherited Wolfenb\u00fcttel and in 1416 divided their lands: Henry retained L\u00fcneburg and Bernard kept Wolfenb\u00fcttel until 1428, when exchanged it with L\u00fcneburg from his nephews.\n|-bgcolor=\n||1400-1409|| [[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] and [[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Wolfenb\u00fcttel]]\n|-bgcolor=#F8F8D8\n||1409\u20131416|| [[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] \n|-bgcolor= \n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Bernard I, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Bernard I]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[File:BernhardIvonbraunschweig-l\u00fcneburg.jpg|100px]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|between 1358 and 1364\n|bgcolor=#F8F8D8|1388\u20131400\n|rowspan=\"3\"|11 June 1434\n|bgcolor=#F8F8D8| [[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] \n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Margaret of Saxe-Wittenberg]]<br/>1386<br/>three children<br>\n|-bgcolor=\n||1400\u20131409|| [[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] and [[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Wolfenb\u00fcttel]]\n|-bgcolor=#D8F8D8\n||1409-1428|| [[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Wolfenb\u00fcttel]]\n|-bgcolor=#88EEEE\n|[[Otto II, Duke of Brunswick-G\u00f6ttingen|Otto VI ''the One-Eyed'']] || ||1380||1394\u20131463||6 February 1463||[[Principality of G\u00f6ttingen|G\u00f6ttingen]] ||[[Agnes of Hesse]]<br/>1408<br/>one child|| With no male heirs, after his death Gottingen is absorbed by [[Principality of Calenberg|Calenberg]].\n\n|-bgcolor=\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[William the Victorious, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|William IV ''the Victorious'']]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[File:Wilhelmdersiegreiche.jpg|100px]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|1392\n|bgcolor=#F8F8D8|1416\u20131428\n|rowspan=\"4\"|25 July 1482\n|bgcolor=#F8F8D8| [[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] \n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Cecilia of Brandenburg]]<br/>30 May/6 June 1423<br/>[[Berlin]]<br/>two children<br><br>[[Matilda of Holstein-Pinneberg]]<br/>1466<br/>one child\n|rowspan=\"6\"| Sons of Henry III, ruled jointly. In 1428 they exchanged, with their uncle Bernard I, L\u00fcneburg for Wolfenb\u00fcttel. In 1432 founded the Principality of Calenberg, a split-off from L\u00fcneburg, and left the remaining Wolfenb\u00fcttel to his brother Henry IV. After the latter's death William took his lands. In 1463, attached the [[Principality of G\u00f6ttingen]] to Calenberg.\n|-bgcolor=#D8F8D8\n||1428\u20131432|| [[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Wolfenb\u00fcttel]]\n|-bgcolor=#FFDAED\n||1432\u20131482|| [[Principality of Calenberg|Calenberg]] (and [[Principality of G\u00f6ttingen|G\u00f6ttingen]]) \n|-bgcolor=#D8F8D8\n||1473\u20131482|| [[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Wolfenb\u00fcttel]]\n|-bgcolor=\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Henry the Peaceful, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Henry IV ''the Peaceful'']]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1411\n|bgcolor=#F8F8D8|1416\u20131428\n|rowspan=\"2\"|7 December 1473\n|bgcolor=#F8F8D8| [[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] \n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Helena of Cl\u00e8ves]]<br/>1436<br/>one child\n|-bgcolor=#D8F8D8\n||1428-1473|| [[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Wolfenb\u00fcttel]]\n|-bgcolor=#B3B7FF\n|[[Henry III, Duke of Brunswick-Grubenhagen|Henry V]] ||||1416||1427\u20131464||20 December 1464||[[Principality of Grubenhagen|Grubenhagen]] (Part 1 from 1440)|| [[Margaret of \u017baga\u0144]]<br/>before 27 June 1457<br/>two children|| In 1440 divided Grubenhagen with his brother Albert.\n|-bgcolor=#F8F8D8\n|[[Bernard I, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Bernard I]]||[[File:BernhardIvonbraunschweig-l\u00fcneburg.jpg|100px]]||between 1358 and 1364||1428\u20131434||11 June 1434|| [[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] ||[[Margaret of Saxe-Wittenberg]]<br/>1386<br/>three children<br>|| In 1428, Bernard recovered Luneburg from his nephews.\n|-bgcolor=#F8F8D8\n|[[Otto I the Lame|Otto VII ''the Lame'']]||[[File:Ottovonbraunschweig-lueneburg(gest.1446).jpg|100px]]||?||1434\u20131446||1446|| [[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] ||[[Elisabeth of Eberstein]]<br/>1425<br/>one child<br>\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Ruled jointly. Their rule was marked by major building work to Celle Castle and also by numerous reforms which improved the legal situation of farmers vis-a-vis their local lords.\n|-bgcolor=#F8F8D8\n|[[Frederick II, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Frederick II ''the Pious'']]||[[File:Friedrichderfromme.jpg|100px]]||1418||1434\u20131457||19 March 1478|| [[Principality of L\u00fcneburg|L\u00fcneburg]] ||[[Magdalene of